post_text:
The Boys & Girls Zizzer Cross Country & Track teams competed at Willow Springs last night with both teams winning the championship title!

Riley Simpson was the individual winner in the boys' race with Justin Fleetwood in second. Also scoring for the boys and helping them earn a low score of 19 points were Brodie Callahan, Drew Stewart, and Ridge Smith.

In the girls' race, Brayden Kantola was once again the individual champion. She was followed closely by sister and teammate Jordan Kantola, who was the runner up and in third place was Jayna Gunter.

West Plains also had two individual winners in the JV Races in Natalie Stewart and Zacch Viers.

The teams will compete again on Saturday at Nixa in the Nixa Quad Invitational. #ZizzerPride

post_text:
The West Plains School District is excited to announce free breakfast and lunches to ALL students preschool through 12th grade!! ‚Üí

Beginning September 14, 2020 all students preschool - 12th grade enrolled in online, virtual, seated or hybrid learning will receive free meals through the end of the fall semester. The free meals are made possible due to an extension of waivers allowed by the USDA. The district in conjunction with Opaa! Food Management, Inc., will provide the free breakfasts and lunches. To continue programs such as this, the district encourages parents and guardians to continue to complete and submit Free/Reduced Lunch applications. For more information on meal distribution, or free/reduced meal applications, or to find out how virtual students can utilize the meal program, visit www.zizzers.org.

post_text: The West Plains School District will move to a hybrid learning model for students grades 7-12 on September 14. To best prepare for this process, students in grades 7-12 will not report to school on September 8-11, 2020. This will enable the district to modify schedules, procedures, and allow our instructors to prepare for the hybrid learning model. Preschool-6th grade students will report and continue to learn in the classroom next week and throughout the fall 2020 semester. For full details, visit www.zizzers.org

post_text:
The West Plains Middle School 5th grade students gathered to remember and honor someone present in each of their lives - 'I can‚Äôt.' The students reflected on all things they believe they ‚Äòcan‚Äôt' do and then made lists. The students put the ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt‚Äôs‚Äù to rest by shredding them during a make-shift funeral service.

The students remembered ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt‚Äôs‚Äù life by the reading of an eulogy. ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt‚Äù is survived by his siblings; ‚ÄòI Will,‚Äô ‚ÄòNot Yet,‚Äô ‚ÄòI Can‚Äô and ‚ÄòI am Going To Do It Right Away.‚Äô This school year the words of ‚ÄòI Can,‚Äô ‚ÄòI Will,‚Äô ‚ÄòNot Yet‚Äô and ‚ÄòI am Going To Do It Right Away‚Äô will become more familiar with the students than the word ‚ÄòI CAN‚ÄôT.‚Äô The students will work to believe in the power of ‚Äúyet‚Äù and are excited to believe, persevere, and learn about new, motivating ways to try new things.

Remember, Wednesdays we release one hour early. Happy second day of school!

In an effort to shift focus from teaching to learning, the district has designated time in the 2020-2021 calendar to allow teachers at all grade levels to work together.

Each week on Wednesdays beginning on August 26, all buildings will dismiss one hour early. This dedicated, weekly time will be devoted to teacher collaboration through the Professional Learning Communities school improvement model. For more information on PLC, visit https://www.zizzers.org/domain/1100.

post_text:
OMC/Zizzer Clinic Now Open on West Plains School District Campus ‚Üí

Ozarks Medical Center opened a new healthcare clinic located on the West Plains School District campus on August 24.

The OMC/Zizzer Clinic is a unique healthcare model in which comprehensive physical and preventative healthcare services are provided to school-aged youths and school staff in the school setting. It is a result of a collaboration between the West Plains School District and OMC to support the student population's healthcare needs.

The OMC/Zizzer Clinic is open Monday to Friday from 7:30 a.m. until 4:30 p.m., for appointments and walk-ins, even when school is not in session. It is located at 1013 College St., West Plains. Please call 417-505-7123 with any questions, or to make an appointment.

For more information, visit www.zizzers.org

post_text: We are so exited for this opportunity!
shared_text:
Ozarks Medical Center
August 24 at 7:51 AM ¬∑

OMC opens School-based Healthcare Clinic at West Plains School District beginning on the first day of school on August 24.

OMC/Zizzer Clinic is a unique healthcare model in which comprehensive physical and preventative healthcare services are provided to school-aged youths and school staff in the school setting. It is a result of a collaboration between the West Plains School District and OMC, to support the healthcare needs of the student population ~ because healthy students are healthy
learners.

OMC/Zizzer Clinic will be open Monday to Friday from 7:30 a.m. until 4:30 p.m., for appointments and walk-ins. It is located at 1013 College St., West Plains. Beginning August 24, please call 417-505-7123 with any questions, or to make an appointment.

#ZizzerNation

post_text:
Tomorrow will be exciting; tomorrow is a new day; tomorrow is finally here.

Even with all the preparation, there will be bumps tomorrow. Buses will run late, drop-off & pick-up will move slowly, phones will be busy, and there will be computer issues.

But know this, our staff will take care of our children - we will start building relationships and we will do all we can to make sure they're safe. Our #ZizzerFamily will make it happen.

Let's all show grace, kindness & patience to support each other through this big day!

#ZizzersReturnToLearn #ZizzerCommunity #ZizzersStrongerTogether #ZizzerPride

Download Your First Day of School Signs!!

The West Plains School District is making it easy for families and staff to take a customized photo on the first day of school (Aug. 24). Simply download a sign and take a photo. We are collecting first-day photos to share on our social media platforms. Families and staff can use the hashtag #ZizzersReturnToLearn to share photos with the first-day signs. Make sure the posts are public so we can find them. Upload the photos by noon on Wednesday August 25, and the district will share as many as possible to celebrate the first day back.

Click Here to Download https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1yAkz_jJXu6dAxWLYUaqYEsXe-iNhxg4C

post_text:
Reminder -

In the 2020-2021 school year, the West Plains Elementary will begin at 7:30 am and end at 2:55 pm. South Fork Elementary will start at 8:00 am and end at 3:45 pm. West Plains High School and Middle School will begin at 8:05 am and end at 3:40 pm.

In an effort to shift focus from teaching to learning, the district has designated time in the 2020-2021 calendar to allow teachers at all grade levels to work together. Each week on Wednesdays beginning on August 26, all buildings will dismiss one hour early. This dedicated, weekly time will be devoted to teacher collaboration through the Professional Learning Communities school improvement model. For more information on PLC, visit https://www.zizzers.org/domain/1100.

We have some amazing paraprofessionals on our team! This morning they are working to help organize and distribute school supplies!

This year the West Plains Education Foundation provided the following school supplies for all seated PreK-8 students: (Supplies will be distributed to students on the first day of school.)

- Big Erasers
- Pencils
- Glue Sticks
- Crayons ‚Äì Elementary grades
- Colored Pencils ‚Äì Middle School Grades
- Composition Notebooks ‚Äì Elementary Grades
- 5 Subject Notebooks - Middle School Grades

Please note, high school students will receive a list of recommended items at open house or the first day of school.

Thank you to the West Plains Education Foundation for providing these items for our students.

#ZizzerPride #ZizzersReturntoLearn

post_text:
Many students in the West Plains area need assistance each year with back to school items. On Saturday, August 22, the Bridges Program will host a Back to School & Health Fair to provide students with shoes, clothes, backpacks, hygiene items, and other resources to help them be successful in school.

This year the fair will be drive-through only with attendees entering East Main Street beginning at 9:00 a.m. Those who are preregistered will be admitted first. The fair is open to students who are attending West Plains School District, Fairview, Glenwood, Howell Valley, Junction Hill, Richards, or Head Start.

Visit www.zizzers.org to register.

In an effort to shift focus from teaching to learning, the district has designated time in the 2020-2021 calendar to allow teachers at all grade levels to work together. post_text:
The West Plains High School is scheduled to host prom for our 2019 -2020 juniors and seniors; because the district is hosting prom, we must follow CDC social distancing guidelines and of the facility, including wearing a mask. Last week, we sent a survey to all juniors and seniors asking their opinion on prom. We gave students three options: to wear a mask at prom, to host a different event other than prom, or to simply cancel prom. The survey results overwhelmingly say our students want to have prom and are willing to wear a mask. The West Plains High School will host prom on Friday, July 24 and will follow CDC guidelines, including wearing a mask. More information regarding prom will be announced in the next week. Stay tuned.

#ZizzerPride #ZizzersStrongerTogether

Once a Zizzer, Always a Zizzer! #ZizzerPride

West Plains Elementary Preschool/Kindergarten Screening Information

West Plains Elementary Preschool Screening ‚Äì June 16 - Location ‚Äì West Plains Elementary

West Plains Elementary Kindergarten Screening- June 17 & June 18 ‚Äì Location ‚Äì West Plains Elementary

Please provide:
*Birth Certificate
*Immunization Records
*Proof of Residency

Children entering preschool must be four before August 1, 2020.
Children entering kindergarten must be five before August 1, 2020.

An appointment must be made in advance for screenings. Please call 417-256-6158 to schedule an appointment. Each screening should take approximately 1 hour and 15 minutes.

The July session of the West Plains School District summer school program will offer different options to tailor your child‚Äôs learning experience to work best for your family. Elementary, middle school, and high school students may choose from a fully virtual experience, seated classes, or a blend of online and seated classes (July 6-30).

For more information on registration, classes, meals, transportation or on general expectations, please visit www.zizzers.org.

We look forward to seeing your child at summer school in July!

After serving meals to our students since March and throughout COVID19, the West Plains School District is now beginning to see a considerable decrease in demand. Thursday, June 11, is the last day for meal pickup. The district will discontinue Grab & Go Food Pickup at all locations.

The Bridges Program will continue to serve families in need of food and hygiene items. If you or someone you know needs help, please stop by Bridges on Wednesdays from 10:00 a.m. ‚Äì 11:30 a.m. at 1013 North College Street (right across from the district transportation department).

West Plains School District Has Served More Than 163,000 Meals In Last Two Months

post_text:
163,474 ‚Äì That‚Äôs the number of meals served to our students during COVID-19.

At the beginning of COVID-19, the West Plains School District immediately saw a need to feed our students and partnered with OPAA to serve breakfast and lunch Monday through Friday. 163,474 meals have been served to our kids over the last two months, through bus routes and Grab & Go Pickup locations.

We want to take the opportunity to thank Opaa!, and our food service crew for getting up early and preparing the meals each day. We want to thank our teachers for helping to deliver the meals, our bus drivers for driving the buses, our custodial crew for helping to load, and all of our dedicated staff who have made this happen. There are many employees working behind the scenes to ensure we serve our community and our kids.
#ZizzersStrongerTogether

post_text:
Important Change to the West Plains School District Meal Distribution Plan

Beginning Monday, June 1, the West Plains School District‚Äôs Bus Stop Meal Service will change to Grab & Go Pickup only. Meals will be distributed from 10:30 a.m. to 11:30 a.m., Monday through Thursday with double meals on Thursday. The distribution locations are OMC Thrift Store, high school tennis courts, United Freewill Baptist Church parking lot (Lanton Road), and the South Fork Elementary parking lot.

The meal service is open to all children 18 years of age and under. No ID or paperwork is required to participate. The program is designed to ensure students have access to healthy meals while school is not in session.

West Plains High School FBLA State Leadership Virtual Conference Results

Aaron Brooks, a West Plains High School Senior and a Future Business Leaders of America (FBLA) member, recently competed virtually for the Missouri Future Business Leaders of America ‚Äì Phi Beta Lambda State Leadership Conference.

Aaron finished in 6th place in the State in Impromptu Speaking. Aaron had to give his speech via a Zoom call. He was given a speech prompt and had 10 minutes to prepare before delivering his speech. Congratulations, Aaron! Well done! #ZizzerPride #FBLA

post_text:
The West Plains Elementary and the West Plains Middle School were recently recognized as Nationally Distinguished PLTW - Project Lead The Way (PLTW) schools. The West Plains Elementary is one of only 238 schools nationally to receive this award, and the West Plains Middle School is one of 157.

The PLTW recognition program is designed to honor districts and schools committed to increasing student access, engagement, and achievement in their PLTW programs. The West Plains Elementary and West Plains Middle School are empowering students to thrive in an evolving world and have achieved exemplary results from their PLTW programs.

Congratulations!! Way to go! #PLTW

West Plains High School Graduation Plans

The West Plains High School is set to provide a modified graduation ceremony with reduced numbers to comply with local and state ordinances and to observe safe interaction while providing the best possible ceremony for our graduates.

The Class of 2020 will have its commencement ceremony on Saturday, June 6, at 10:00 a.m. at the Zizzer Stadium. This will allow the class of 2020 to graduate together at the football stadium. To comply with local rules, only six guests will be admitted. Additional details on graduation will be released tomorrow morning.

Congratulations to our West Plains School District Make a Difference Award winner, Raegan Fox! Raegan is a counselor at the West Plains High School.

The Make a Difference Award recognizes a member of the district educational community for their efforts in supporting the diverse needs of students academically, socially, and emotionally in a variety of learning settings. The award recognizes those who help to support an atmosphere of continuous learning and growth for all students and provides excellence in support of meeting the diverse needs of all students.

Thank you for all you do, Raegan! You are so appreciated. #ZizzerPride #ZizzersStrongerTogether

post_text:
***Edit - Pick will be at the high school tennis courts.

No Cooking - No Cleaning Monday, May 4 - Dinner Courtesy of Bootleggers BBQ

Bootleggers BBQ has teamed up with Operation BBQ Relief to serve 10,000 meals to our community in 10 days. Bootleggers has already served meals to members of our community, emergency personnel, front line workers, nursing homes, and hospitals. Now they want to serve you!

On Monday, May 4 Bootleggers will set up at the West Plains High School tennis courts and provide approximately 2,500 meals to the community from 4:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m. Simply drive through, give the number of meals you wish to receive, pick up and enjoy at home. No cooking! No cleaning! **First Come, First Serve.

Please be sure to thank Bootleggers for providing this treat. It is a huge undertaking for them and has taken their entire team hours extra to prepare. We appreciate Bootleggers for thinking of all of us, and we are, #ZizzersStrongerTogether

post_text: Congratulations to Abigail Yarber and Charlie Huddleston on being named Zaner-Bloser National Handwriting Contest State winners. Abigail is a third-grader, and Charlie Huddleston is a fifth-grader at South Fork Elementary. The contest gives students in kindergarten through eighth grade the chance to showcase and receive recognition for their handwriting skills in manuscript or cursive. About 280,000 students nationwide participated in this year‚Äôs contest. Abigail and Charlie will receive an award when school is back in session. Congratulations to both Abigail and Charlie on this great achievement! #ZizzerPride

We want to show you what distance teaching looks like. post_text:
Loaded up and hitting the road!

Over 3,500 breakfasts and lunches are on the way to our kids this morning. Special thanks to our custodial crew for your dedication and determination to feed our kids every single day. We are so thankful for you and all of our hard-working faculty and staff. #ZizzersStrongerTogether

All children 18 and under can receive meals through our Bus Stop Meal Service & Grab-and-Go Food Pickup. The meals will be in one bag and delivered between 9:45 a.m. and 11:30 a.m., Monday through Friday. (Please visit www.zizzers.org for the exact times and locations for your children). If you are unsure of your delivery location or have issues obtaining meals from the bus stops, please call the district transportation office at 256-7525.

The district will also continue to provide Grab-and-Go Food pick up at the high school tennis courts and the OMC Thrift store from 10:00 a.m. to 11:30 a.m.

post_text:
5 Day Learning Plans ‚Üí

We realize the classroom experience cannot be replicated, and that Learning Plans are not a substitute for direct instruction. Still, we hope it will provide structure and normalcy, as well as continuity of learning and connection to our students.

Because of the recent and local Covid19 developments, the next round of 5 Day Learning Plans will only be available via email and accessible online (www.zizzers.org). The 5 Day Learning Plans will be available beginning Tuesday, April 7. If we discover through this process, your email is not functioning; we will reach out to obtain the correct email address. For parents and students, without access to email or the internet, the packets will be mailed or delivered through bus routes. On Monday, April 6, each building will provide a drop off bin to return Learning Plans for the weeks of March 25 and March 30. These packets will be quarantined and then distributed. Please visit www.zizzers.org/covid19 for more information.

post_text:
Bus Stop Meal Service & Grab-and-Go Food Pickup for Students ‚Üí

Beginning tomorrow, March 26, the West Plains School District and our food service provider Opaa! Food Management, Inc. will start serving meals to all students through our bus routes. Every West Plains School District child will have the opportunity to have breakfast and lunch delivered at their regular bus stop, Monday through Friday. The meals will be in one bag and delivered between 9:45 a.m. and 11:30 a.m. (Please visit www.zizzers.org/covid19 for the exact times and locations for your children). We ask that everyone is patient, especially in the first few days, while we are figuring out the logistics. We will adjust the delivery times and routes if necessary. If you are unsure of your delivery location or have issues obtaining meals from the bus stops, please call the district transportation office at 256-7525.

The district will also continue to provide Grab-and-Go Food pick up at the high school tennis courts and the Ozarks Medical Center Thrift store.

Me: Today is Wag Wednesday for Virtual Spirit Week. We are supposed to take a walk and I am supposed to take a picture of us on the walk.
Lucy: Ummmm..... scratch a little to the left.
Me: I think getting you out of the house might be a good idea.
Lucy: Scratch a little to the right. That's it! That's the spot.
Me: You know, it could just be the way you are laying, but it looks like you have some new, ummmm, rolls.
Lucy: What are you trying to say? Say it. What are you saying?
Me: Nothing.
Lucy: Is that your camera? Did you just take a picture of me? ARGH! NO! DON'T PUSH SHARE! DON'T PUSH SHARE!
#ZizzersStrongerTogether

For Lucy's Lessons, please go to the third grade drop down and find the lesson entitled "What To Do?" Discuss the life changing scenarios with your child to determine what they would do and introduce what they should do. The link is in the comments below.

The Bridges Program is open for families in need of food and hygiene items. Program director Cyndi Wright and her team have been busy packing bags of groceries to help our community. If you or someone you know could use a little extra help, please stop by Bridges Monday through Friday at 10:00 a.m. ‚Äì 11:30 a.m. at 1013 North College Street (right across from the district transportation department).

**The Bridges program is a West Plains School District project. It is a community-based organization designed to help meet students' needs in the West Plains School District and the surrounding rural schools, leading to children being able to focus on their education. For more information about the Bridges program or to donate, please call 417-256-6155.

On March 19, the district was informed by the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education (DESE) that required statewide assessments (MAP, End of Course Exams, etc.) are canceled for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. We want to reassure you that even though the state has canceled mandated testing, the district will continue to provide educational resources. Detailed information will be available early next week. Details regarding required assessments for graduating seniors are still being explored. As soon as we have additional information, we will communicate the information with you.

DESE also informed us that school districts are not required to make up the calendar hours lost through April 3 due to the extended school closure caused by COVID-19.

The district will continue to communicate regularly with the entire Zizzer family throughout this extended school closure. We will send frequent updates with information and resources via our website, district app, email, text messages, and social media channels.

post_text:
Congratulations to these students on becoming a 2020 white coat recipient! To earn a white lab coat, students must earn a B or higher in 3 semesters of Project Lead the Way (PLTW) biomedical science classes. The lab coats have chevron(s) on the right sleeve for every biomedical class they have taken, badges on the left sleeve for every class they have earned college credit for, and their full name on the front. A very special thank you to Ozarks Medical Center for sponsoring the program.

Way to go - Kendra Collins, Avery Watson, Kendall Wynn, Joshua Lunyou, Shonti Addison, Gabriel Huddleston, Ellie Cropper, Quinn Curtis, Madison Rost, and Staci Allcorn!

#ZizzerPride #ZizzerCommunity #PLTW

post_text: Alexis Brown, a West Plains High School senior, participated in the Family, Career and Community Leaders of America (FCCLA) Legislative Shadowing Project on Wednesday. The program provides an opportunity for junior and senior high school students to spend a day with a state representative, a senator or other public official at the State Capitol. Alexis spent the day with Representative David Evans. The students observe hearings, meetings, and public duties. The event is designed to help students develop a better understanding of the political process and its impact on citizens. Way to go, Alexis! #ZizzerPride
